<br>
Unmezzable Mobs - Simply swop out mez for a debuff, perhaps Cripple or Weakness (yes the level 44 one). If my memory serves Weakness reduces mob STR by 65, no small amount. Otherwise I will load a DD or DoT.<br>
<br>
As I've levelled I've even found situations where the group have 'learned' that suchandsuch mob is unmezzable e.g. rock golems in Hole, and they rush to tank it without thinking that the level of their chanter can make a whole HEAP of difference. It took several shouts of 'But I OUTRANK IT' before they learned to not break my mez.<br>
<br>
Mobs that Outclass You - This becomes much less of an issue at 55, disappearing by 60 in average exp groups. Here is where aggro control and mana management win the day. <br>
<br>
Aggro Control - Whether it's keeping the mob off you, your cleric, your over zealous wizzy or keeping it on your tank who is taunting for dear life and still not managing to hold aggro.<br>
<br>
Knowing when to sit, stand, where to stand, when to cast, what to cast is as important as having the right spells loaded. We learn early on not to sit when a mez is about to be broken and it takes discipline to not back off when you're getting beat on, as well as trust in your MA - hands up all who at least once in their early chanter career have run OOR for a heal. Here is definitely where root earns its spell slot...land it, step back and let the natural laws of Proximity Aggro take over. <br>
<br>
I also use all the new aggro spells much more now in exp groups, preferring Calming Visage to reduce aggro and Horrifying to increase - using them both you can play with up to 40% of mob hate list. But I'm still learning a lot about the exact effects of these spells and they still feel situational at the moment.<br>
<br>
Mobs that Train - yes please, more of them in every dungeon. Classic CC skills, AE mez, talk to your shaman / cleric and work with them to back up root if you need it. Line 'em up and feed 'em to your tanks one by one...I adore training mobs and my MA soon learns to set up an /assist Gladriel hotkey if they don't already have one. <br>
<br>
Using Charm - Perhaps risky in full groups where the cleric has a lot to pay attention to, unless there is a shaman or druid back up healer. If there is, I will nominate them my personal healer and go fetch a mob to charm - they enjoy it, so do I. Most often, I use charm when I duo with a particular cleric friend and using charm we can clear about half of Velks Tents mobs before repops...even a named Kobold there duoing with a hasted and buffed kob warrior pet only.<br>
<br>
There are some dungeons I wouldn't walk into without a specific spell memmed, in addition to the 5 that I always keep up. These would be...<br>
<br>
Velks - AE mez<br>
Sebilis - ToT, AE Mez or Charm<br>
Chardok - ToT, AE mez<br>
HS - AE mez<br>
For anything unknown, but anticipated to be tough, I always load GoK, Dazzle, Root and AE mez - maybe overkill, but I want to KNOW I can stop a mob in its tracks and buy enough time for the group to figure out what to do.<br>
<br>
